@node play "The game: Installation/Playing"

                             Installation

  The installation is very simple, just place "Permu" where you
want on your hard drive, floppy disk, Ram Disk, etc. No other files
or Libraries are needed. The only requirement is that your
Workbench must have at least 8 colours.

NOTE: As I am not sure of this game's 'behaviour' on a stock 68000
      Amiga. For now, until somebody confirms that Permu runs
      fine on a 68000 machine, this game will require an Amiga
      with a 68020 or faster processor... sorry!

                             How to play?

  To play, click on any tile, except the ones in the leftmost
column and those on the uppermost row (clicking on these tiles
will have no effect). The tile you selected will exchange its
position with the one located on the upper left on the board.
Also, all the tiles in the same row at the left will permutate,
the same procedure goes for all the tiles that are located over
your clicked tile.

  Here's an example of a typical game board permutation:

                   a . b .   @{b}Note@{ub}: the letters represent coloured
                   . . c .         tiles and the '.' are other
                   . . d .         tiles that are ignored in this
                   e f g .         example.
                       ^
                       ^
                       Clicked tile

  The result:

                   g . d .
                   . . c .
                   . . b .
                   f e a .

  ...so the letters 'b c d', 'a g' and 'e f' changed positions
(note that the letter 'c' in the 'b c d' series didn't move
because it was located in the center of the permutation).

  Anyways, it's much more simple to play the game than it is to
explain how it works, so try it!

  Have fun!

OPTIONS:

  You can choose the game board size by clicking on the arrows or
'+', '-', '>' or '<' signs, located on the upper right or lower
left of the board.

  The arrows pointing up or to the right next to the '@{b}+@{ub}' sign, are
used to enlarge the board in the direction they are pointing. In
addition, the '+' sign can be used to simultaneously increase both
height and width of the board. If the board is already at its
maximum size, clicking on the '+' sign or the associated arrows
will have no effect.

  The arrows pointing down or to the left next to the '@{b}-@{ub}' sign
decrease the size of the board. Also, you can use the '-' sign to
decrease both width and height of the board, unless either the
width or height already are at their minimum.

  If you don't want to use the arrows or just want the biggest or
smallest board, you can click on the '<' or '>' icons which will
display the smallest or biggest board.

  You can restart the game any time by clicking on the 'New Game'
button.

  You can quit the game by clicking on the main window's close
button or by pressing on the 'Esc' key.

